    <p>
        <m>{\color{black} \textbf{Key Takeaway:}}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        An open cylinder has a curved surface and one circular face.
    </p>
    <p>
        Therefore, 
    </p>
    <p>
        <md>
            <mrow>\textbf{Surface area of an open cylinder } = \amp \pi r^2 +2 \pi rh </mrow>
            <mrow>= \amp {\color{blue} \pi r (r+2h)} </mrow>
        </md>
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Note:}</m> For an open cylinder an exeminer will give guidlines. 
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                An open cylindrical cotainer has a height of <m>12\,cm</m> and a diameter of <m>2\,cm</m>. What is the surface area of the outer 
                surfaces of the container? (<m>\textbf{Use} \, \pi = 3.142</m>)
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                You are given the height and diameter of the container to be <m>h=12\,cm \, \textbf{and} \, d=2\,cm</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                You first identify the radius of the container that is,
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> r=\amp \frac{2}{2} </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 1 \,cm</mrow>
                   
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore,
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{surface area}=\amp \pi r (r+2h)</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 3.142 1(1+2 \times 12) </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 3.142 1(1+24) \,cm</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 3.142 \times 25 \,cm</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 78.55\,m^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, surface area of the outer container is <m>={\color{blue} 78.55\,m^2}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Ekadeli filled an open cylindrical bucket with water. The internal diameter of the bucket was <m>32.4 \,cm</m> 
                and the internal height was <m>35 \,cm</m>. Calculate the area of the bucket that was in contact with the water. 
                Write the answer correct to <m>\textbf{1 decimal place}</m>. (<m>\textbf{Use} \, \pi =\frac{22}{7}</m>)
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The open cylindrical bucket has a diameter and height of <m>d=32.4\,cm \quad \text{and} \quad h=35\,cm</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                You first calculate the radius of the cylindrical bucket which is,
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> r=\amp \frac{d}{2} </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp  \frac{32.4}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 16.2 \,cm</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore,
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Surface area} =\amp \pi r (r+2h) </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{22}{7} \times 16.2 \,cm (16.2\,cm+2\times 35\,cm) </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp  \frac{22}{7} \times 16.2 \,cm(16.2\,cm+70\,cm)</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{22}{7}  \times 16.2 \,cm\times 86.2 \,cm  </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 4388.81142857\,cm^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The surface area <m>={\color{blue} 4388.8\,cm^2}</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The surface area of an open jar is <m>594\,cm^2</m>. The radius of the jar is <m>7\,cm</m>. 
                calculate the height of the jar. (<m>\textbf{Use} \, \pi =3.142</m>).
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                You are given,
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\textbf{Surface are}=594\,cm^2</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>r=7\,cm</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>h=</m>?
            </p>
            <p>
                To find the height of the jar we substitute the above values in the formula below.
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Surface area}=\amp \pi r (r+2h) </mrow>
                    <mrow> 594\,cm^2=\amp \frac{22}{7} \times 7\,cm (7\,cm +2\times h)</mrow>
                    <mrow> \frac{594}{22}=\amp 7\,cm +2\times h</mrow>
                    <mrow> \frac{594}{22}-7=\amp 2 \times h </mrow>
                    <mrow> 20 =\amp 2 \times h</mrow>
                    <mrow> \frac{20}{2}=\amp h</mrow>
                    <mrow>h= \amp 10 \,cm </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The height of the jar <m>={\color{blue} 10 \,cm  }</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
   
  


    




 



    
